{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}} {{Use Australian English|date=July 2013}} {{Infobox rugby league biography |name = Cyril Abotomey |fullname = Cecil Phillip Abotomey |nickname = Cyril |image = |imagesize = |caption = |birth_date = 1902 |birth_place = [[White Cliffs, New South Wales]] |death_date = 20 December 1980 |death_place = [[Brisbane, Queensland]] |height = |weight = |position = {{Rlp|CE}} |club1 = [[Sydney Roosters|Easts]] ([[New South Wales Rugby League premiership|Sydney]]) |year1start = 1923 |year1end = 24 |appearances1 = 21 |tries1 = 4 |goals1 = 2 |fieldgoals1 = 0 |points1 = 16 |updated = |source = }} '''Cecil "Cyril" Abotomey''' (1902-1980) was an Australian rugby league footballer for the [[Sydney Roosters|Eastern Suburbs]] club of the [[New South Wales Rugby League]] competition.
Abotomey wasa Paddington junior in Rugby League and Cricket and also played junior Australian Rules football for the Double Bay side.<ref>The Arrow, 9 June 1917, p.2</ref> In Rugby League he played in both the [[Rugby league positions|centre]] and [[Rugby league positions|wing]] positions and was a member of Eastern Suburbs 1923 [[1923 New South Wales Rugby League premiership final|premiership winning side]]. Abotomey was also a member of the Eastern Suburbs side that won the President's Cup in 1922, and is officially recognised as Eastern Suburbs 138th player. He eventually moved to Brisbane and continued his career there. He died in Brisbane in 1980 and was buried at the Toowong Cemetery on 22 December 1980.
