{{Infobox officeholder |name = Edward Aloysius Kenney |image = Edward Aloysius Kenney (New Jersey Congressman).jpg |caption = Frontispiece of 1938's ''Edward Aloysius Kenney, Late a Representative'' |state = [[New Jersey]] |district = {{ushr|New Jersey|9|9th}} |term_start = March 4, 1933 |term_end = January 27, 1938 |predecessor = [[Peter Angelo Cavicchia]] |successor = [[Frank C. Osmers Jr.]] |birth_name = |birth_date = {{Birth date|1884|8|11}} |birth_place = [[Clinton, Massachusetts]] |death_date = {{Death date and age|1938|1|27|1884|8|11}} |death_place = [[Washington, D.C.]] |party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] }}
'''Edward Aloysius Kenney''' (August 11, 1884 &ndash; January 27, 1938) was a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[New Jersey]].
==Biography== Kenney was born on August 11, 1884 in [[Clinton, Massachusetts]] and attended the [[Clinton Public School District|public schools]]. He graduated from [[Clinton High School (Clinton, Massachusetts)|Clinton High School]] in 1902. He then graduated from [[Williams College]] in 1906, and from the law department of [[New York University]] in [[New York City]] in 1908. He was admitted to the [[New York State Bar Association]] in 1908 and commenced practice in New York City. He moved to [[Cliffside Park, New Jersey]] in 1916 and continued the [[practice of law]].
During the [[World War I|First World War]] he served as a member of the legal advisory [[draft board]] of New Jersey in 1917. He was judge of recorders court in [[Cliffside Park, New Jersey]], from 1919-1923. He was an unsuccessful candidate for [[Mayor of Cliffside Park, New Jersey]] as an Independent in 1921, as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] in 1923, and as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] in 1927.
He became chairman of the Cliffside Park Housing Commission in 1922 and 1923 and was a member of the Republican county committee in 1925 and 1926.
Kenney was elected as a Democrat to the [[73rd United States Congress|Seventy-third]], [[74th United States Congress|Seventy-fourth]], and [[75th United States Congress|Seventy-fifth]] [[United States Congress|Congresses]] and served from March 4, 1933, until his death in [[Washington, D.C.]] due to an accidental fall from a window on January 27, 1938.
He is buried in St. John’s Cemetery, Clinton, Massachusetts.
