'''Eloi Baribeau''' (December 1, 1906 &ndash; July 28, 1957) was a business owner and politician in [[Quebec]]. He served as mayor of [[Gatineau, Quebec]] from 1956 to 1957.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://craoutaouais.ca/repertoire/Web/Barib-Elo.html |title=Eloi Baribeau |work=Répertoire des élus municipaux de l’Outaouais de 1845 à 1975 |publisher=Archives nationales du Québec|language=fr}}</ref>
The son of former Gatineau mayor [[Théodore Baribeau]] and Lucia Lacroix, he was born in [[Lac-Sainte-Marie, Quebec]] and was educated at [[Collège Bourget|Bourget College]] in [[Rigaud, Quebec|Rigaud]]. He moved to Gatineau Mills, later part of Gatineau, with his parents in 1928 and afterwards opened a service station there. In 1940, Baribeau married Lucienne Charron. He served nine years on Gatineau council before becoming mayor in 1956. Baribeau died in office when he drowned after falling out of a boat in Whitefish Lake near [[Gracefield, Quebec|Gracefield]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2194&dat=19570729&id=OrcxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=teMFAAAAIBAJ&pg=7354,2856822 |title=Gatineau Mayor Drowned Despite Efforts of Son |newspaper=Ottawa Citizen |date=July 29, 1957 |page=9}}</ref>
